    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>BANK SETTLES SECURITIES VIOLATIONS</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Timothy Pritchard</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Pritchard, Timothy</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Pension management division of Royal Bank of Canada, in settlement with Ontario Securities Commission, agrees to pay fine of 3 million Canadian dollars ($2 million) and pressures seven senior officers and traders to resign; Toronto Stock Exchange has also levied suspensions and 400,000 Canadian dollars in fines against 12 traders involved in transactions; division, RT Capital, admitted to pushing up price of shares with trades late in the day to artificially raise performance of its portfolio (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>In a settlement with the Ontario Securities Commission for unlawful stock trading, the pension management division of the Royal Bank of Canada has agreed to pay a fine of 3 million Canadian dollars ($2 million) and pressured seven senior officers and traders to resign. The Toronto Stock Exchange has also levied suspensions and 400,000 Canadian dollars in fines against 12 traders involved in the transactions. The division, RT Capital, admitted to pushing up the price of shares with trades late in the day to artificially raise the performance of its portfolios.</p>
        <p>Timothy Pritchard (NYT)</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>In a settlement with the Ontario Securities Commission for unlawful stock trading, the pension management division of the Royal Bank of Canada has agreed to pay a fine of 3 million Canadian dollars ($2 million) and pressured seven senior officers and traders to resign. The Toronto Stock Exchange has also levied suspensions and 400,000 Canadian dollars in fines against 12 traders involved in the transactions. The division, RT Capital, admitted to pushing up the price of shares with trades late in the day to artificially raise the performance of its portfolios.</p>
        <p>Timothy Pritchard (NYT)</p>
        <p>WORLD BUSINESS BRIEFING: AMERICAS</p>
      </block>
